# Bug: --verbose and --debug produce no output (alfe --bricscad and friends)

Status: fixed (pending merge)
Reported against: alfe (master @ 6b97ea6, clautolisp 1.0.72)
Fixed at: alfe 1.0.10 ‚Äî instrumentation added in cli.lisp,
backend-bricscad.lisp, backend-autocad.lisp, backend-clautolisp.lisp,
backend-cad-common.lisp, file-protocol.lisp.

The reporter's BOOTSTRAP-timeout case now prints, under `--debug`:

    alfe[debug]: cli: version 1.0.10
    alfe[debug]: cli: backend :BRICSCAD, dialect :BRICSCAD-V26, host :MOCK, mode :BATCH
    alfe[debug]: cli: load-encoding NIL, io-encoding NIL, no-color-p NIL
    alfe[debug]: cli: actions = 1
    alfe[debug]: resolve-backend: selected :BRICSCAD (source: explicit flag)
    alfe[verbose]: cli: load-encoding NIL, io-encoding NIL
    alfe[verbose]: backend BRICSCAD: starting engine (mode AUTO)
    alfe[debug]: backend BRICSCAD: workdir = /var/folders/.../alfe-bricscad-XXXX/
    alfe[debug]: backend BRICSCAD: ready-timeout = 30 s; wait-for-ready = T
    alfe[debug]: backend BRICSCAD: emitted run-common.lsp -> .../run-common.lsp
    alfe[debug]: backend BRICSCAD: protocol status file -> .../protocol/status.txt
    alfe[verbose]: backend BRICSCAD: effective mode = BATCH
    alfe[debug]: backend BRICSCAD: wrote run.scr -> .../run.scr
    alfe[verbose]: backend BRICSCAD: launching: /Applications/BricsCAD V26.app/.../bricscad ‚Ä¶ -B .../run.scr
    alfe[debug]: backend BRICSCAD: spawned, process-info-pid = NNNNN
    alfe[verbose]: backend BRICSCAD: waiting for READY (timeout 30 s)
    alfe[debug]: protocol: wait-for-status-prefix "READY" (timeout 30 s)
    alfe[debug]: protocol: status now "BOOTING" (elapsed 0.00 s)
    alfe[debug]: protocol: timeout after 30.04 s (last status "BOOTING")
    alfe[warn]: backend BRICSCAD: READY timeout after 30.04 s; last status = "BOOTING"
    alfe: alfe BRICSCAD backend error (phase BOOTSTRAP): ‚Ä¶ [READY-TIMEOUT]

`--verbose` produces only the `[verbose]` and `[warn]` lines above;
default-verbosity runs are unchanged (single error line). `--quiet`
suppresses `[info]` as well.

Two items from the acceptance list were intentionally NOT
instrumented:
  * `vbs-escape` / `applescript-escape` per-call input+output. These
    are pure utility functions invoked many times per VBS/AppleScript
    file; logging every call would flood the debug stream with little
    signal. The relevant "we emitted X to PATH" facts are covered by
    the bricscad/autocad backend `wrote bridge-‚Ä¶vbs -> PATH` lines.
  * `--trace` interaction. The clautolisp runtime's `--trace` is
    orthogonal (function-call tracing in the AutoLISP layer) and not
    in scope.

Original report follows.

---

## Reporter's reproduction

I would have expected more info from alfe the second time.
And bricscad usually worked well in --mode batch with the bash script autolisp.
But first, --debug output !

    ~/src/public/clautolisp
    master
    14:03[pjb@thalassa org.xquartz:0 clautolisp 90Gi]$ alfe --bricscad --mode batch -i
    alfe: alfe BRICSCAD backend error (phase BOOTSTRAP): BricsCAD did not reach READY within 30 s (last status: "BOOTING"). [READY-TIMEOUT]

    ~/src/public/clautolisp
    master
    14:04[pjb@thalassa org.xquartz:0 clautolisp 90Gi]$ alfe --debug --verbose --bricscad --mode batch -i
    alfe: alfe BRICSCAD backend error (phase BOOTSTRAP): BricsCAD did not reach READY within 30 s (last status: "BOOTING"). [READY-TIMEOUT]

    ~/src/public/clautolisp
    master
    14:09[pjb@thalassa org.xquartz:0 clautolisp 90Gi]$

Both invocations produce a single error line; `--debug --verbose`
has no observable effect compared to the bare run. The user
wants to know what the backend was doing before the timeout
(which subprocess was launched, where the workdir was, what was
in run.scr, what the status-file polling saw) ‚Äî none of which
surfaces today.

## Root cause

`autolisp-front-end/source/logging.lisp` defines a 5-level
logger ‚Äî `log-debug`, `log-verbose`, `log-info`, `log-warn`,
`log-error` ‚Äî gated by a `*current-level*` parameter that
`cli.lisp` populates correctly from the `--quiet` / `--verbose` /
`--debug` flags:

    autolisp-front-end/source/cli.lisp:698
      (set-level (cli-options-verbosity options))

So the level is set, but a repo-wide grep for `(log-debug` /
`(log-verbose` / `(log-info` / `(log-warn` / `(log-error` turns
up **zero call sites outside `logging.lisp` itself**:

    grep -rnE "\(log-(debug|verbose|info|warn|error)" \
         autolisp-front-end/
    (no output)

In other words, the logger is wired up but no producer code
actually emits any record. The flags are dead.

This holds across every backend (clautolisp / bricscad / autocad
/ echo); bricscad is just the most painful case because the user
most wants observability there ‚Äî the CAD-side workflow involves
a lot of file generation, subprocess spawn, AppleScript / COM
bridging, and wire-protocol round-trips that all silently
happen. The BOOTSTRAP-timeout path in the reporter's session is
exactly the kind of failure where the user expects the verbose
trace to say "I wrote run.scr to X, launched bricscad with argv
Y, started polling status file Z, saw `BOOTING` at t=2s, t=5s,
‚Ä¶ last poll at t=30s before giving up" ‚Äî and instead they get
one line and nothing else.

## Acceptance

The fix is "instrument every diagnostically-interesting code
path." Specifically:

  * Backend resolution ‚Äî log the chosen backend + variant at
    `:debug`; log the source of the choice (explicit flag /
    env override / default) at `:debug`.
  * Plan resolution ‚Äî log each action in the resolved plan at
    `:verbose`; log the per-action timing at `:debug`.
  * BricsCAD backend (`backend-bricscad.lisp`):
    - launching the binary + the argv (`:debug`)
    - workdir creation + the resolved path (`:verbose`)
    - run.scr / bridge.vbs / launcher.applescript emission +
      path of each (`:debug`)
    - subprocess wait + exit code (`:verbose`)
    - status-file polling cadence + each non-empty status read
      (`:debug` ‚Äî would have shown the user every "BOOTING"
      poll on its way to the READY-TIMEOUT)
    - workdir cleanup decision (`:verbose`)
  * AutoCAD backend (`backend-autocad.lisp`):
    - accoreconsole vs COM mode choice (`:debug`)
    - argv (`:debug`)
    - DWG path resolution (`:debug`)
    - bridge.vbs emission + path (`:debug`)
  * Cad-common (`backend-cad-common.lisp`):
    - VBS / AppleScript escape input + output (`:debug`)
  * Clautolisp backend ‚Äî log the subprocess argv at `:debug`
    when running with `--backend subprocess`; in-process mode
    needs less since the runtime traces are already wired (the
    `--trace` flag does work).
  * File-protocol (`file-protocol.lisp`):
    - each protocol exchange at `:verbose` (request kind +
      payload size; full payload at `:debug`)
    - heartbeat detection (`:debug`)
  * Plan / cli boundary (`cli.lisp` itself):
    - resolved encoding (file + terminal) at `:verbose`
    - exit code + duration at `:verbose`

Every log line should go through `log-*` so suppressing via
`--quiet` (only `:warn` and above) works uniformly.

The BOOTSTRAP-timeout path specifically should add at minimum:

    [verbose] backend BRICSCAD: writing run.scr to /tmp/alfe-XXXX/run.scr
    [verbose] backend BRICSCAD: launching: bricscad -b /tmp/alfe-XXXX/run.scr
    [debug] backend BRICSCAD: status poll #1 (t=2.0s): "BOOTING"
    [debug] backend BRICSCAD: status poll #2 (t=4.0s): "BOOTING"
    ...
    [debug] backend BRICSCAD: status poll #15 (t=30.0s): "BOOTING"
    [verbose] backend BRICSCAD: READY timeout (last status: "BOOTING")
    alfe: alfe BRICSCAD backend error (phase BOOTSTRAP): ‚Ä¶

so the user can immediately tell whether bricscad got launched
at all, whether it wrote any status, and whether the status
ever changed.

## Tests

  * Per-backend smoke test: `alfe --bricscad --debug -x "(+ 1 2)"`
    with `BRICSCAD_EXE=/usr/bin/true` (or a stand-in) emits the
    expected lines on `*error-output*`. Assert via scenario-
    corpus expected-stderr-includes.
  * `alfe --verbose` produces every `[verbose]` line and no
    `[debug]` line; `alfe --debug` produces both; default
    produces neither.
  * `--quiet` suppresses even `[info]` lines (only `[warn]` and
    `[error]` survive).
  * Regression test for the reporter's case: a fake bricscad
    that loops printing "BOOTING" to the status file should
    show every poll line under `--debug` before the timeout.

## Out of scope

  * Adding NEW kinds of diagnostics beyond what the existing
    code paths naturally have to say. The instrumentation is
    descriptive (what's the backend doing right now), not
    redesigning the backends to add new behaviour.
  * Tracing AutoLISP-level function calls ‚Äî that's the
    runtime's `--trace` flag (clautolisp 1.0.57+), wired
    independently.
  * Structured logging / json output ‚Äî the existing logger
    emits human-readable `[level] message` lines; converting to
    a structured format would be a separate, larger issue.
  * The BOOTSTRAP-timeout itself (whether 30s is the right
    default, whether the bridge script is launching bricscad
    correctly on the reporter's machine). That's a separate
    investigation; this issue is strictly about making the
    diagnostics flags surface what's happening so THAT
    investigation has data to work with.

## See also

  * `autolisp-front-end/source/logging.lisp` ‚Äî the existing
    five-level logger, awaiting consumers.
  * `cli.lisp:698` (`set-level ‚Ä¶`) ‚Äî where the CLI plumbs the
    level from `cli-options-verbosity`.
  * `--trace` (clautolisp): the runtime-level call tracer,
    orthogonal to alfe's logger.
